82","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","1298":"1298","1328":"1328","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tong, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1325–":"1325–Deceased","1297–1315":"1297–1315","1298–Female":"1298–Deceased","1299–Female":"1299–Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","1301–Female":"1301–Deceased","1325–Female":"1325–Deceased","1320–1345":"1320–1345","1345–1382":"1345–1382","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1283–Female":"1283–Deceased","1297":"1297","1340":"1340","1283":"1283","1382":"1382","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1301":"1301","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1320":"1320","1298":"1298","1328":"1328","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England":"Tong, Shropshire, England","Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cheyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Japanese: written 井伊 ‘well’ and ‘that’, the name one of Japan's great daimyō families, originally based in Tōtōmi (now part of Shizuoka prefecture), later in Kōzuke (now Gunma prefecture) and Ōmi (now Shiga prefecture). Other variants of the name substitute either character with similar sounding characters such as 飯 ‘cooked rice’, 居 ‘residence’, and so forth. It was formerly Romanized as <b>Iyi</b>. — Note: In the population figure published by the US Census Bureau, the Roman number <i>II</i> (meaning ‘the second’, i.e. ‘the younger’ of the two bearers of the name) is apparently also counted as a surname <i>Ii</i>.","History: Ii Naomasa (1561–1602) was awarded lands in Kōzuke and Ōmi for his service in the civil wars that won the shōgunate (military dictatorship) for Tokugawa Ieyasu. His family built the beautiful castle of Hikone, which still stands. His descendant Ii Naosuke (1815–1860) ruled Japan for two years as Tairō (Great Elder) and played a major part in signing treaties that opened Japan to foreign trade at the end of the Tokugawa Shōgunate. He was assassinated by adherents of the anti-foreign party."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isolda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The name of the tragic mistress of Tristan in the Arthurian romances. There are several versions of the story. The main features are that the beautiful Isolde, an Irish princess, is betrothed to the aged King Mark of Cornwall. However, through accidentally drinking a magic potion, she and the young Cornish knight Tristan fall in love, with tragic consequences. The story has exercised a powerful hold on the European imagination. The name was relatively common in Britain in the Middle Ages, but is much rarer today."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isolda De Cheyne II was born in 1325, in Shropshire, England, her father, Mr. Cheyne, was 21 and her mother, Mrs. Isabel Cheyne, was 42. She married Roger de Cheyne II in 1340, in Tong, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1325–":"1325–Surnud","1297–